        "last_activity_date": 1720749134,
        "creation_date": 1520964694,
        "answer_count": 3,
        "title": "Is Java&#39;s EnumSet mutable?",
        "body": "<p>Is there any way to modify an <code>EnumSet<\/code> object? It seems that (for example) <code>EnumSet.add<\/code> is inherited from <code>AbstractSet<\/code> and that throws an <code>UnsupportedOperationException<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Yet it looks as if <code>EnumSet<\/code> is modifiable; otherwise why bother having a <code>clone()<\/code> method, and why would Guava have <code>Sets.immutableEnumSet()<\/code>? Is there a method of <code>EnumSet<\/code> that's escaped my mind?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 49263098,
        "tags": ["java"],
        "score": 7,
        "accepted_answer_id": 49263193,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 4400
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/V0ki9.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 10670591,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 7855784,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7855784/subash-j",
                "reputation": 2058,
                "display_name": "Subash J"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 7,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1720748943,
            "creation_date": 1520965026,
            "body": "<p>Yes <code>EnumSet<\/code> is modifiable. If you want to create an immutable <code>EnumSet<\/code> then go for <a href=\"https://guava.dev/releases/snapshot/api/docs/com/google/common/collect/Sets.html#immutableEnumSet(java.lang.Iterable)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">immutableEnumSet<\/a>.<\/p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Returns an immutable set instance containing the given enum elements. Internally, the returned set will be backed by an <code>EnumSet<\/code>.<\/p>\n<p>The iteration order of the returned set follows the enum's iteration order, not the order in which the elements appear in the given collection.<\/p>\n<h6>Parameters:<\/h6>\n<p><code>elements<\/code> - the elements, all of the same <code>enum<\/code> type, that the set should contain<\/p>\n<h6>Returns:<\/h6>\n<p>an immutable set containing those elements, minus duplicates<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 49263193,
            "question_id": 49263098,
            "last_edit_date": 1720748943
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/72UnO.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 5553464,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4405757,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4405757/thiyagu",
                "reputation": 17970,
                "display_name": "Thiyagu",
                "accept_rate": 57
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 5,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1720749087,
            "creation_date": 1520965538,
            "body": "<p><code>EnumSet<\/code> is just an abstract class. Its implementation overrides the <code>add<\/code> method which makes it mutable and hence the below is possible.<\/p>\n<pre><code>EnumSet&lt;MyEnum&gt; enumSet = EnumSet.of(MyEnum.A);\nenumSet.add(MyEnum.B);\n\n\nprivate static enum MyEnum {\n   A,B,C;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 49263318,
            "question_id": 49263098,
            "last_edit_date": 1720749087
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a42f8ff287eb5abf432ce696bf7c653b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 115767,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 303810,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/303810/lexicore",
                "reputation": 43917,
                "display_name": "lexicore",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1720749134,
            "creation_date": 1520966168,
            "body": "<p><code>EnumSet<\/code> is an abstract class which has implementations <code>RegularEnumSet<\/code> and <code>JumboEnumSet<\/code>. Both implement <code>add<\/code> and are mutable. <code>EnumSet.of(...)<\/code> choose <code>RegularEnumSet<\/code> or <code>JumboEnumSet<\/code> depending on the number of enums.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 49263520,
            "question_id": 49263098,
            "last_edit_date": 1720749134
        }
    ],
